== Overview == The name "Shiotsuchi" can be interpreted as "Master of the Tides" or "Way of the Tides," associating the deity with control over tidal currents and navigation. In {{ill|Kiki mythology|ja|記紀神話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiki mythology|qq=}}, Shiotsuchi no Oji plays a critical role, offering guidance and information to key figures. His portrayal as a coastal deity who imparts wisdom has parallels to the "Old Man of the Sea" motif found in {{ill|Greek mythology|ja|ギリシア神話|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Greek mythology|qq=}}, such as {{ill|Proteus|ja|プローテウス|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Proteus|qq=}}. Additionally, he is revered as a god of salt production.
The shrine tradition of {{ill|Shiogama Shrine|ja|鹽竈神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiogama Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Shiogama|ja|塩竈市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiogama|qq=}}, {{ill|Miyagi Prefecture|10=ja|11=宮城県|ja|宮城県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyagi Prefecture|qq=}}, regards him as the deity who guided {{ill|Takemikazuchi|ja|タケミカヅチ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takemikazuchi|qq=}} and {{ill|Futsunushi|ja|フツヌシ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futsunushi|qq=}} during their pacification of the land. Shiotsuchi no Oji remained in the area to teach fishing and salt production to the people, making him a prominent deity in these domains.
== Legends == In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}’s account of the {{ill|Descent of the Heavenly Grandson|ja|天孫降臨|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Descent of the Heavenly Grandson|qq=}}, Shiotsuchi no Oji is identified as {{ill|Kotosakukuni Katsunagasa|ja|事勝国勝長狭神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotosakukuni Katsunagasa|qq=}}. He offers his land to {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ninigi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ninigi|ja|ニニギ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninigi|qq=}} upon his arrival at Kasasa Cape. Another tradition identifies him as a son of {{ill|Izanagi|ja|イザナギ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Izanagi|qq=}}.
In the myth of {{ill|Umisachi and Yamasachi|ja|山幸彦と海幸彦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Umisachi and Yamasachi|qq=}}, Shiotsuchi no Oji assists {{ill|Hoori|ja|ホオリ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hoori|qq=}}, who had lost his brother's fishing hook. He provides a small boat (or tightly woven basket) and instructs Hoori to let the tides guide him to the palace of the sea deity {{ill|Watatsumi|ja|ワタツミ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watatsumi|qq=}}.
During the {{ill|Eastern Expedition of Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武東征|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eastern Expedition of Emperor Jimmu|qq=}}, the Nihon Shoki recounts that Shiotsuchi no Oji inspired Emperor {{ill|Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jimmu|qq=}} to head east, stating, "There is good land to the east."
== Shrines == Shiotsuchi no Oji is enshrined at notable shrines, including: * {{ill|Shiogama Shrine|ja|鹽竈神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiogama Shrine|qq=}} (Shiogama City, Miyagi Prefecture) – The main shrine. * {{ill|Shiogama Shrine (Tokyo Minato)|ja|鹽竈神社 (東京都港区)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiogama Shrine (Tokyo Minato)|qq=}} (Tokyo) * {{ill|Takamu Shrine|ja|高室神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takamu Shrine|qq=}} (Kakegawa City, Shizuoka Prefecture) * {{ill|Rokusho Shrine (Okazaki)|ja|六所神社 (岡崎市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokusho Shrine (Okazaki)|qq=}} (Okazaki City, Aichi Prefecture) * {{ill|Rokusho Shrine (Toyota)|ja|六所神社 (豊田市)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Rokusho Shrine (Toyota)|qq=}} (Toyota City, Aichi Prefecture) * {{ill|Shioya Shrine (Hiroshima)|ja|塩屋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shioya Shrine (Hiroshima)|qq=}} (Hiroshima City, Hiroshima Prefecture)
